[[cdo:11 nguŏk 21 hô̤ (nùng-lĭk)]] [[de:November 21 (Lunisolar)]] [[sn:November 21 (Lunisolar)]] [[ko:음력 11월 21일]] [[ja:11月21日 (旧暦)]] [[zh:十一月廿一]] [[en:draft:November 21 (Lunisolar)]] [[en:11月21日 (旧暦)]] [[sn:ovember 21 (Lunisolar)]] [[ar:November 21 (Lunisolar)]]

{{afc comment|1=This article as with the other date articles is relatively limited in scope to Japan. Reviewing the translation of this is good and also adding content translated from Chinese and Korean wikipedias will also be good. Both wikipedias are also relatively centered around their own countries for their Lunisolar calendar dates[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 00:16, 28 April 2025 (UTC)}} {{Globalize|article|Japan|date=April 2025}} {{Expand Chinese|1=十一月廿一|topic=hist|date=April 2025}} {{Expand Korean|1=음력 11월 21일|topic=hist|date=April 2025}} {{Lunisolar November|qq=}} '''November 21''' is the 21st day of the month {{ill|November (Lunisolar)|ja|11月 (旧暦)|lt=November (Shimotsuki)|qq=|qq=draft}}, the 11th month of the traditional {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=|qq=draft}}. Its {{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜|qq=|qq=draft}} day is {{ill|Senshō|ja|先勝|qq=|qq=draft}}.
== Events == * {{ill|Ninna|ja|仁和|qq=|qq=draft}} 3rd year（[[Julian calendar]] [[887]] [[December 9]]） – The Daijō-daijin and Fujiwara Mototsune were appointed as {{ill|Kanpaku|ja|関白|fr|Kanpaku|ru|Кампаку|sv|Kampaku|uk|Кампаку|zh|關白|qq=|qq=draft}}, becoming the first commoner Kanpaku. * {{ill|Tenkei|ja|天慶|qq=|qq=draft}} 2nd year ([[Julian calendar]] [[940]] [[January 3]]） – Taira no Masakado attacked the Hitachi provincial government, seizing official seals and capturing Hitachi-no-kasuke and Fujiwara Noriaki. * [[承徳]] 1st year ([[Julian calendar]] [[1097]] [[December 27]]） – Due to a celestial event, the era name was changed from Eichō to Shōtoku. * [[乾元 (日本)|乾元]] 1st year ([[Julian calendar]] [[1302]] [[December 10]]） – The era name was changed from Seian to Kangen for the accession of Emperor Go-Nijō. * [[安永]] 8th year（[[Gregorian calendar]] [[1779]] [[December 28]]） – Hiraga Gennai was imprisoned on suspicion of accidentally killing two of his disciples. * {{ill|Genji|ja|元治|qq=|qq=draft}} 1st year ([[Gregorian calendar]] [[1864]] [[December 19]]） – The Tokugawa shogunate signed the "Yokohama Residence Memorandum" with Britain, the United States, France, and the Netherlands.
== Births == * [[En'ō]] 1st year ([[Julian calendar]] [[1239]] [[December 17]]） – Fujiwara Yoritsugu, the 5th shogun of the Kamakura shogunate (d. [[1256]]). * {{ill|Kyōhō|ja|享保|qq=|qq=draft}} 18th year ([[Gregorian calendar]] [[1733]] [[December 26]]） – Makino Sadanaga, a politician (d. [[1796]]). * {{ill|Enkyō|ja|Enkyō|qq=|qq=draft}} 4th year ([[Gregorian calendar]] [[1747]] [[December 17]]） – Arakida Hisao, a kokugaku scholar (d. [[1804]]). * {{ill|Bunkyū|ja|文久|qq=|qq=draft}} 3rd year ([[Gregorian calendar]] [[1863]] [[December 31]]） – Nagase Tomorō, the founder of Kao (d. [[1911]]). * [[Meiji era|Meiji]] 3rd year ([[Gregorian calendar]] [[1871]] [[January 11]]） – Taoka Reiun, a writer and critic (d. [[1912]]).
== Deaths == * [[Bunmei]] 13th year ([[Gregorian calendar]] [[1481]] [[December 12]]） – Ikkyū Sōjun, a Zen monk (born [[1394]]). * {{ill|Man'en|ja|万延|qq=|qq=draft}} 1st year ([[Gregorian calendar]] [[1861]] [[January 1]]） – Asaka Gensai, a Confucian scholar ({{ill|Ru (Confucian scholar)|ja|儒学者|zh|儒生|qq=|qq=draft}}) (born [[1791]]).
